Let R be a Ring. Let x\neq 0 be a nonzero element of R. We say x is:

a Left Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq  0 and xy=0;

a Right Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq  0 and yx=0;

a (Two Sided) Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq 0 and xy=0 and yx=0.
The way to remember left and right zero divisors is which side x appears.

Consider \varepsilon \in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{2}(\mathbb {C}) defined as
\varepsilon =\begin {pmatrix}0 & 1\\ 0 & 0\end {pmatrix}
We see that \varepsilon ^{2}=0. Hence \varepsilon  is a zero divisor.

If x is a left zero divisor, then there is a y\in  R such that xy=0. But if x were also a unit, then
\begin {align*}0&=x^{-1}0\\ &=x^{-1}(xy)\\ &=(x^{-1}x)y\\ &=1y=y\end {align*}
which contradicts the condition that y\neq 0 in the definition of a zero divisor.

(1) We can extend this to as many unknowns as we want, writing R[x_{1},…,x_{n}] or even R[x_{1},…,x_{n},…] for infinitely many unknowns. Then the sums make use of Multi-index notation. For example, for R[x,y] we have
p(x,y)=\sum ^{n}_{|\alpha |=0}a_{\alpha }x^{\alpha _{1}}y^{\alpha _{2}}
and so on.

Let R be a nonempty Commutative Ring. Let x_{1}, …, x_{m} be formal variables. Let
p(x) = \sum ^{n}_{|\alpha |=0}a_{\alpha }x^{\alpha }
be a formal polynomial, i.e., p\in  R[x_{1},…,x_{m}] with some \alpha  having |\alpha |=n being such that a_{\alpha }\neq 0. Then we define the Degree of p to be the non-negative integer \deg (p) equal to n.

Suppose \vec {0}' is another zero vector. Then
\vec {0}'=\vec {0}'+\vec {0}=\vec {0}+\vec {0}'=\vec {0}
hence \vec {0}=\vec {0}'.

We see
v+(-1)v=1v+(-1)v=(1+(-1))v=0v=\vec {0}
by Scalar multiples of zero vector are the zero vector.

Let V be a finite-dimensional real vector space with a well-defined notion of a dot product. Let B be an orthogonal basis of V. We call B an Orthonormal Basis of V if for all f\in  B we also have f\cdot  f=1. In other words, we have for all f_{i},f_{j}\in  B,
f_{i}\cdot  f_{j}=\delta _{i,j}
where \delta _{i,j} is the Kronecker delta.

Let V be a finite-dimensional real vector space. Let B=(f_{1},…,f_{n}) be an Ordered Basis of V. Then we call the n coefficients \lambda _{1},…,\lambda _{n}\in \mathbb {R} such that
v = \lambda _{1}f_{1}+…+\lambda _{n}f_{n}
are called the Coordinates of v relative to B. We can write this down as a column vector:
[v]_{B} = \begin {pmatrix}\lambda _{1}\\\vdots \\\lambda _{n}\end {pmatrix}
for the coordinates of v relative of B.

Let V be a finite-dimensional real vector space. Let u,v\in  V be vectors. Assume u\neq \vec {0}. We define the Projection of v along the u direction to be the vector
\mathrm {Proj}_{u}(v)=\frac {u\cdot  v}{u\cdot  u}u=(\widehat {u}\cdot  v)\widehat {u}
where \widehat {u}=u/\sqrt {u\cdot  u} is the unit vector in the u-direction.

This is a linear transformation since \mathop {	extrm {id}}
olimits _{V}(c_{1}u+c_{2}v)=c_{1}u+c_{2}v=c_{1}\mathop {	extrm {id}}
olimits _{V}(u)+c_{2}\mathop {	extrm {id}}
olimits _{V}(v).

Let b_{1},b_{2}\in  A be inverses for a. Then
\begin {align} b_{1}&=\mu (b_{1},e)\\ &=\mu (b_{1},\mu (a,b_{2}))\\ &=\mu (\mu (b_{1},a),b_{2})\hbox { by associativity}\\ &=\mu (e,b_{2})\\ &=b_{2}.\end {align}
Hence the result.

